@startuml State_URL_Lifecycle
!theme blueprint
title URL Shortener — URL Lifecycle State Diagram

skinparam stateBackgroundColor #f0f4ff
skinparam stateBorderColor #6366f1
skinparam stateArrowColor #6366f1

[*] --> Created : POST /api/shorten\nBase62 encode + cache

state Created {
    state "is_active = true\nclick_count = 0\nshortCode set" as C1
}

Created --> Active : immediately after creation

state Active {
    state "Serving redirects\nTracking clicks\nCached in Redis" as A1
}

Active --> Active : GET /{shortCode}\nclick_count++\nlog access event

Active --> Expired : expiryTime < now\n(checked on each request\nOR by scheduled job)

Active --> Deleted : DELETE /api/{shortCode}\nis_active = false\nevict from Redis

state Expired {
    state "is_active = true\nexpiryTime in past\nreturns 410 Gone" as E1
}

state Deleted {
    state "is_active = false\nreturns 404\nRedis key evicted\nanalytics preserved" as D1
}

Expired --> Cleaned : @Scheduled job\nruns every hour\nbatch soft-delete\nclear Redis keys

state Cleaned {
    state "is_active = false\nDB record kept\nurl_access_logs kept\nhistory preserved" as CL1
}

Deleted --> [*] : record stays in DB\nfor analytics history
Cleaned --> [*] : record stays in DB\nfor analytics history

note right of Active
    Redis cache TTL = 24h
    On cache miss → DB query
    On Redis failure → fallback to DB
    (fault tolerant)
end note

note right of Expired
    HTTP 410 Gone
    (semantically correct —
    resource existed but
    is no longer available)
end note

note right of Deleted
    Soft delete — is_active = false
    Hard delete never used.
    Analytics data preserved forever.
end note

@enduml
